# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: breast-binding
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The **2020s anti-LGBTQ movement in the United States** is an ongoing political backlash from social conservatives and the "MAGA" faction of the Republican Party against LGBTQ movements, and in particular against transgender rights.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] It has included legislative proposals of bathroom use restrictions, bans on gender-affirming care, anti-LGBTQ curriculum laws, attacks on inclusive language, laws against drag performances, book bans, boycotts, and conspiracy theories about grooming.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Between 2018 and 2026, thousands of anti-LGBTQ laws were considered, drawing heavily from the British anti-trans movement, with more than one hundred passed into law.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Targeting of transgender people escalated under the second Donald Trump administration.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The backlash has been described as a moral panic, and part of a larger culture war in the United States.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Scholars have cited rising anti-LGBTQ attitudes and policies as an example of democratic backsliding in the United States.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The backlash has been connected to similar right-wing developments in Europe, Canada, as well as the Middle East.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Usage of this term increased in the 2020s.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In the United States, the popularization of the term was linked to Christopher Rufo and James A.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Following the Wi Spa controversy in July 2021, Julia Serano said a rise in false accusations of grooming directed towards transgender people was a movement to "lay the foundation for just smearing all trans people as child sexual predators".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Teachers and parents have also been accused of being or enabling groomers.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The conspiracy theory moved into the American conservative mainstream in spring 2022, including its use by members of the Republican Party, the Heritage Foundation, and far-right extremists and conspiracy theorists.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] This has been described as a moral panic and a smear.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In July 2022, a wave of anti-LGBTQ curriculum resurgence saw ten such laws beginning to take effect in six different states: Florida, Indiana, South Dakota, Tennessee, Utah and Alabama.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Some states enacting these new laws appear to have mirrored similar laws from other states.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In Florida, the Parental Rights in Education law and Florida Board of Education policy bans education on "sexual orientation" or "gender identity" unless it is mandated under state academic standards or as part of an optional reproductive health course or lesson.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In August 2023, the state of Florida dropped AP Psychology as a course offering, due to a required section on sexual orientation and gender identity.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The same month, Tampa-area schools announced they would restrict the teaching of William Shakespeare's works in order to comply with the Parental Rights in Education law.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Alabama bans LGBTQ topics for kindergarten to grade 5, except for instruction deemed "age or developmentally appropriate".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Five other states (Montana, Arizona, Arkansas, Tennessee and Florida) require parental notification of instruction on LGBTQ issues and allows parents to opt-out of such instruction.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In California (where state law requires students to learn about the "role and contributions" of LGBTQ people in history), multiple protests against the inclusion of LGBTQ-friendly curriculum resulted in violence.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] At a June 2023 protest in Glendale, individuals seen protesting LGBTQ curriculum were identified as members of hate groups, such as the Proud Boys.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] State and local officials in the South used indecency and obscenity laws to ban books from school libraries.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In June 2021, the Biden administration reinforced that Title IX protected LGBTQ students from discrimination by including sexual orientation and gender identity in its list of protections.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In August 2021, Tennessee and nineteen other states sued the Department of Education in *Tennessee v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Department of Education*, alleging that the new Title IX governance constitutes government overreach.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] A preliminary injunction was granted by a Tennessee judge in July 2022, blocking enforcement of the new guidance.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2022, the Department of Education appealed the decision, which is still pending.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The new guidance was rejected by the Florida Department of Education, calling the guidance a "sexual ideology" that risks the "health, safety, and welfare of Florida students".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] As many as 13 U.S. states banned gender affirming health care for transgender youth in the early-2020s.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Many Republican legislators across the country are increasingly proposing legislation that would restrict gender-affirming care for adults or make such treatments harder to access.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] However, unlike for minors, no states have fully banned gender-affirming care for adults.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Efforts to restrict adults' access to healthcare rely heavily on claims from self-described "gender-critical" organizations such as Genspect that young people should not be recognized as adults until they turn 25.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2024, some Republican legislators in Ohio and Michigan expressed their desire to ban gender-affirming healthcare altogether, saying their 'endgame' was to ban it completely for people of all ages.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In July 2025, Puerto Rico became the first place in the United States to pass a ban on gender-affirming care for people over 18, banning it for anyone under 21 years of age.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Puerto Rico's LGBTQ+ Federation immediately announced plans to challenge the ban in court.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Gender-affirming care for minors has been available in the U.S. for more than a decade and is endorsed by major medical associations, but it has increasingly come under attack in many conservative legislatures.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the ACLU, in 2023 alone, over 500 anti-LGBTQ bills were submitted in the US, over 130 of which were about healthcare.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Efforts to prohibit gender-affirming care for minors had begun several years earlier, but did not receive much attention from state legislatures until more recently.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The conservative organization Do No Harm was influential in developing model legislation that appeared starting in 2022 in Arkansas, Florida, Iowa, Mississippi, Montana, New Hampshire, and West Virginia legislatures.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] As of June 2025, 27 states had enacted some form of ban on gender-affirming care for minors, 19 of which were enacted in 2023.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] However, 16 of these bans are being challenged in court as of January 2024.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Furthermore, only 21 of the 27 states have complete bans which are fully in effect.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Four states have only partial bans and two are currently blocked from taking effect.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] While some states have banned all forms of medical transition, others such as Arizona, Nebraska and Georgia have banned only specific types such as hormone therapy or surgery.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Seven states have exceptions which allow minors who were already receiving gender affirming care prior to the ban to continue their treatments.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Currently, all 27 states make exceptions for puberty blockers, hormones and surgery for cisgender and intersex children.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] There is only one state, Missouri, that has a ban which is set to expire after a certain period of time.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Nearly all states with restrictions include specific provisions with penalties for providers and 4 states include provisions directed at parents or guardians.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] An additional 4 states include laws/policies that impact school officials such as teachers and counselors, among others.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Many Democratic states have gone in the opposite direction and enacted laws protecting access to gender affirming care for minors and adults.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] As of June 2026, 18 states and the District of Columbia have enacted "shield" laws.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Of the approximately 1.6 million Americans who are transgender, about 300,000 are under the age of 18.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] As of October 2023, approximately 105,200 transgender youth aged 13 to 17 lived in states where gender affirming care is banned for minors.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] However, around 26,000 of those youth are currently still able to access care in their state due to court orders that prohibit enforcement of the laws.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Conversely, around 146,700 transgender youth live in states that have passed gender-affirming care "shield" laws that support access to care by protecting doctors and parents who prescribe or seek access to medical care for youth.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] An analysis from KFF in late January 2024 estimated that 38% of trans youth between the ages of 13–17 in the United States lived in states with laws limiting youth access to gender-affirming care.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Bans on gender-affirming care have been criticized as governments interfering with the patient-doctor relationship and taking away healthcare decisions from parents and families for their children.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] State level bans on gender-affirming care in the United States have led some families with transgender children to move out of their states.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] On October 17, 2024, Texas attorney general Ken Paxton filed suit against a doctor who allegedly provided gender-affirming care to 21 minors after the treatments had been banned for minors in Texas, the first time that such a suit has been brought in the U.S.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] While all 50 states had previously allowed transgender people to change their legal names and documented genders, many states in the 2020s implemented restrictions.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] These restrictions ranged from requiring sterilization to obtain amended documents, to making it a criminal offense to carry a state ID not matching one's assigned gender at birth.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2025, in response to Executive Order 14168, the U.S. federal government ceased issuing passports which do not align with the birth-assigned sex of U.S. citizens.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Supreme Court would, through its shadow docket in *Orr v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Trump*, allow this measure to remain in effect.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2026, the state government of Kansas passed legislation immediately invalidating driver's licenses and birth certificates which do not align with the assigned sex at birth of their recipients, requiring affected residents to pay for updated documents reflecting their birth sex.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The law was initially vetoed by Democrat governor Laura Kelly, but went into effect after the motion was overruled by the state legislature's Republican supermajority.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Seldin stated that the ACLU expects to challenge the law in court.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Kansas representative Abi Boatman, a transgender woman and Democrat, additionally derided the law as "culture war nonsense" and accused it of contributing to Kansas' human capital flight.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Some U.S. states passed legislation restricting the participation of transgender youth in high school sports or of trans women and girls in women's sports.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] States have banned transgender people from sports under their gender identity in various capacities.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] These states include Texas, Arkansas, Florida, Alabama, Oklahoma, Kentucky, Mississippi, Tennessee, West Virginia, South Carolina, Utah, South Dakota, Montana, Iowa, Arizona, Idaho, Wyoming, Indiana, Louisiana, Kansas, Georgia, North Dakota, New Hampshire, North Carolina, Alaska and Ohio.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The passage of legislation against transgender youth has seen increases in calls to Trans Lifeline, a suicide crisis hotline run by and for transgender people.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Some of these bans only apply to school sports and some only apply to transgender women, but not transgender men.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The US Department of Education has said transgender students are protected under Title IX.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In an early example of an anti-trans bathroom bill, the Public Facilities Privacy & Security Act in North Carolina, was approved as a law in 2016.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The bill, however, sparked widespread condemnation and threats of boycotts, and portions of the measure were repealed in 2017 as part of a compromise between the Democratic governor and Republican-controlled Legislature.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2016, guidance was issued by the U.S.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Departments of Justice and Education stating that schools which receive federal money must treat a student as their gender identity (for example, in regard to bathrooms).
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] This policy was revoked by the Trump administration in 2017.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 2020s, bathroom bills have been proposed and debated in a number of state legislatures.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the American Civil Liberties Union, there are currently 469 anti-LGBTQ bills in the US, most targeting transgender people; an example of which is Kansas SB 180.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Several state bills are based on and closely resemble model legislation provided by the Christian legal organization Alliance Defending Freedom (ADF).
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The ADF's model legislation proposes giving any public school or university student the right to sue for $2,500 for each time they encountered a transgender classmate in a locker room or bathroom.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] A number of the bills put forth and passed made it some form of criminal offense, often a sex offense, for a transgender person to use a bathroom, locker room, changing room, or other similar facility not corresponding with their assigned sex.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The most severe of these was that of Arkansas, which made it an offense of "sexual indecency with a child" for a trans person to use any such facility if said facility contained anyone under 18 at the time of use.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Since 2021, Alabama, Arkansas, Oklahoma, Tennessee, and Idaho have enacted bathroom bills.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] State legislatures in Arizona, Illinois, Kansas, Kentucky, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, South Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas have proposed bathroom bills.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] The National Center for Transgender Equality, an LGBTQ advocacy group, calls these bills discriminatory.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2022, sitting *en banc*, the United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit ruled in *Adams ex rel.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Johns County, Florida* that separating the use of male and female bathrooms in public schools based on a student's biological sex doesn't violate the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment or Title IX of the Education Amendments Act of 1972.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Previously, in August 2020, a three judge panel of the United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit affirmed a 2018 lower court ruling in *Adams v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Johns County* that discrimination on the basis of gender identity is discrimination "on the basis of sex" and is prohibited under Title IX (federal civil rights law) and the Equal Protection Clause of the 14th Amendment to the US Constitution.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2024, Missouri implemented a law discontinuing state funding of gender-affirming care for prison inmates.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] Florida prisons implemented a rule restricting gender-affirming care, and providing psychotherapy to treat underlying mental health issues.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p01] An attorney of the ACLU likened this to conversion therapy.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Additionally, Trump stated that he would make hospitals and health care providers that provide transitional hormones or surgery no longer qualify for federal funding, including Medicare and Medicaid funding.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Trump has also stated he will push to prohibit hormonal and surgical intervention for minors in all 50 states.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Reyes blocked the executive order, ruling that banning trans people from the military likely violated their constitutional rights.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An August 4 United States Air Force memo announced that long-serving transgender members normally eligible for retirement benefits would be denied them.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 28, 2025, Trump signed an executive order to "Protect Children from Chemical and Surgical Mutilation".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The order described gender-affirming care for minors as "chemical and surgical mutilation of children" as well as "maiming" and "sterilizing".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In response, some hospitals paused providing gender-affirming care for minors, while others continued.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Attorneys general from 15 states said their states are committed to continuing to provide gender-affirming care to minors.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Multiple groups filed lawsuits challenging the legality of the executive order.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In response to one of the lawsuits, several federal judges issued injunctions blocking the government from withholding federal funds from hospitals that provide gender affirming care to minors.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Following the injunction, some hospitals that initially paused gender-affirming care for minors resumed the care.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 28, 2025, Trump ordered a freeze on all federal funding grants, loans, and aid while those receiving them were assessed to make sure they were not promoting "advance Marxist equity, transgenderism, and green new deal social engineering policies".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 29, 2025, Trump signed an executive order "Ending Radical Indoctrination in K-12 Schooling".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On February 5, 2025, Trump signed an executive order titled "Keeping Men Out of Women's Sports", which directs federal agencies and state attorneys general to immediately enforce a prohibition of transgender girls and women from participating in women's sports.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The order does not ban transgender men athletes from playing on male sports teams.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] As part of this order's implementation, the Department of Education urged high school and college athletics organizations NCAA and NFHS to revoke female transgender athletes' records and restore cisgender athletes' ones.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The State Department also announced a ban on transgender athletes from entering the United States if they attempt to compete in women's sports, and that visa applicants suspected of such would have their file marked with the letters 'SWS25' for the purposes of tracking.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Visa applicants for any purpose who list a gender other than their assigned sex on their visa application will be permanently banned from entering the United States on grounds of "fraud".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] At the United Nations, the United States under Trump routinely uses their influence action against transgender rights globally, even when unrelated to the topic of discussion.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Both advocates and the Trump Administration have suggested that the United States might use compliance at the UN as a metric for determining which countries receive foreign aid.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Protests against drag performances, especially Drag Queen Story Hour, increased after the 2021 attack at the United States Capitol.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The most vocal opponents are mostly affiliated with alt-right groups.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Former *Fox News* host, Tucker Carlson, suggested that drag events could "indoctrinate or sexualize" children.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Protestors also have expressed homophobic conspiracy theories that performers are grooming children.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The Anti-Defamation League reported that child abuse conspiracy theory has been fueled by the Libs of TikTok, a far-right Twitter account.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation reported over 120 threats against drag shows in the US, throughout 2022.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An Institute for Strategic Dialogue report indicated that the Proud Boys were the leading group spreading anti-LGBTQ sentiment.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On March 2, 2023, Tennessee governor Bill Lee signed the Adult Entertainment Act, which prohibits drag performances for children.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] This bill sparked outrage from the LGBTQ community.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On June 3, 2023, a federal judge ruled that the law is unconstitutional.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On July 18, 2024, a three judge panel on the Sixth Circuit reinstated the law by ruling that the plaintiffs had lacked the standing to sue.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The ruling did not address whether the law was constitutional.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The states of Florida, Montana, and Texas have also passed laws banning public drag performances.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] However, all three of these drag bans were blocked by courts from taking effect.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In response to Executive Order 14168, Texas A&M University and University of Texas systems banned drag shows on campus facilities.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In response to a concurring opinion by Justice Clarence Thomas in *Dobbs v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization* arguing the Court should reconsider *Obergefell v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Hodges*, Congress passed the Respect for Marriage Act in 2022.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The act officially repealed the Defense of Marriage Act and required the federal government to recognize same-sex and interracial marriages, thus codifying parts of *Obergefell,* the 2013 ruling in *United States v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Windsor*, and the 1967 ruling in *Loving v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In addition, it compelled all U.S. states and territories to recognize the validity of same-sex and interracial marriages if performed in a jurisdiction where such marriages are legally performed; however, it does not legally compel states to perform same-sex marriages if *Obergefell* is overturned.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The following year, the Tennessee House of Representatives passed House Bill 878, which would grant an individual the right to refuse to solemnize a marriage if the individual has a religious or conscience-based objection to that partnership.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In Texas, McLennan County Justice of the Peace Dianne Hensley filed a lawsuit to allow her to refuse to marry gay couples, citing the 2023 U.S.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 27, 2025, the Idaho House of Representatives voted for a resolution that calls for the Supreme Court to reconsider its 2015 *Obergefell v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Legislation was introduced or passed in at least 29 states taking aim at lessons that teach children about race and LGBTQ people, with most of the laws framed around putting a stop to critical race theory and "gender ideology".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] These laws, which use broad language prohibiting teaching about privilege related to race or sex, or systemic bias in the United States, have led to many book removals.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] NBC News described the use of the term "critical race theory" in this context as "a catch-all term to refer to what schools often call equity programs, teaching about racism or LGBTQ-inclusive policies".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] *The Takeaway*'s Melissa Harris-Perry cited discomfort with issues like gender identity as one of the common reasons for challenges, but that "this discomfort is likely imposed by adults onto young learners" who are otherwise more accepting and more likely to think outside traditional gender roles.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An example of such bans is that passed by Florida in March 2022, which created a list of sanctioned reading material for students in educational settings, and punished any teacher or school librarian whose classrooms or libraries contained unsanctioned books with felony charges.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Sanctioned books must be reviewed by the state to be free of "prohibited material harmful to minors", which critics have said that under Florida state law includes content regarding the LGBTQ community and black history.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Conservative activists urged for boycotting any company which publicly supported, or collaborated with members of, the LGBTQ community.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Some of the most well-known examples included the boycott against Bud Light for a sponsorship with actress and TikToker Dylan Mulvaney, and the campaign against Disney by Florida governor Ron DeSantis for publicly opposing the state's anti-LGBTQ curriculum law.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Other targeted companies include Nike, Adidas and Ford.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In May 2023, Target removed several Pride Month items from stores in the Southern United States after anti-LGBTQ hate groups threatened violence against its employees.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Following the election of Donald Trump in 2024, Disney removed storylines, episodes, and lines of dialogue that involved transgender characters from several shows set to air.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Under Elon Musk, Twitter declared the words "cis" and "cisgender" to be slurs and banned their usage on the platform, while also eliminating restrictions on transphobia.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Anti-trans content, including PragerU's film *Detrans: The Dangers of Gender-Affirming Care,* has been strongly promoted by the platform.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] *The Nation* described "anti-trans hatred" as one of Twitter's "core features".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] According to a 2023 report by the Department of Homeland Security, threats of violence against the LGBTQ community rose in the early-2020s.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The FBI also noted a sharp uptick in the number of hate crimes committed against LGBTQ people, with the 54 percent increase representing the fastest rise in hate crimes of all groups in the country.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In New York City, hate crimes against LGBTQ people doubled from 2021 to 2022, and grew by 29% in California during the same period.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Violence has also been used against heterosexual people expressing support for LGBTQ rights.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In August 2023, Lauri Carleton, a business owner in Southern California, was shot and killed for keeping a pride flag outside her store.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An April 2021 PBS NewsHour/NPR/Marist poll with the question "Do you support or oppose legislation that would prohibit gender transition-related medical care for minors" found 66% of Americans would oppose a ban, including 69% of Democrats, 70% of Republicans, and 64% of Independents.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A February 2022 poll by LGBTQ support service The Trevor Project and Morning Consult found that 52 percent of American adults expressed some level of support for transgender minors having access to puberty blockers if it is recommended by their doctor and supported by their parents.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] 41% of total Americans held this stance, with 31% disagreeing, and 28% not taking either position.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In a poll from Data for Progress in March 2023, respondents were asked about the more than 400 pieces of anti-trans legislation working their way through statehouses.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] 64 percent of respondents, including 55 percent of Republicans, agreed with the statement "This is too much legislation.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Politicians are playing political theater and using these bills as a wedge issue".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] 25 percent agreed with the statement "This is the right amount of legislation.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A poll by *The Washington Post*/Kaiser Family Foundation, conducted in November 2022, found that 68 percent of adults oppose access to puberty-blocking medication for transgender children ages 10 to 14, and 58 percent oppose access to hormonal treatments for transgender children ages 15 to 17.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In a January 2023 Deseret News/HarrisX poll, 55 percent of Americans supported banning gender hormone therapy for transgender minors with parental or guardian approval, while 45 percent opposed such a ban.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A January 2023 poll by the Pew Research Center found that black Democrats were less likely than other Democrats to believe that a person's gender can be different from their birth sex and more likely to say that their views on LGBTQ issues are determined by their religion.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A May 2023 poll by *The Washington Post*/Kaiser Family Foundation found that a majority of Americans support some anti-trans policies despite also claiming to oppose discrimination for trans people.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2023, a Gallup poll found that only 26% of Americans think trans athletes should be allowed to play on sports teams that match their gender identity.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A September 2023 poll by 19th News/SurveyMonkey found that 39 percent of American adults supported transgender minors having access to any kind of gender-affirming care, including puberty blockers, hormones, therapy, and surgery.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Another poll by The 19th/SurveyMonkey that same month found that in a survey of 20,000 American adults, 17 percent believed politicians should focus on restricting gender-affirming care, while 33 percent believed they should focus on protecting access to gender-affirming care.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The rest believed politicians should not focus on trans issues at all.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A separate poll conducted by The 19th that month found that 7 in 10 Americans, including majorities in both major parties and independents, do not think politicians are informed enough about gender-affirming care to make fair policies on it.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A September 2023 poll conducted by SurveyUSA and sponsored by the anti-trans group, Women's Declaration International, found that a majority of voters believe a person's sex is determined at birth and that sex and gender are the same thing.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] However, it also found that a majority of Americans support laws and policies banning transgender women from women's sports and prisons, prohibiting minors from attending drag shows and creating a law that "defines gender as a person's sex assigned at birth".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Additionally, the survey found that while 54% of Americans oppose allowing transgender minors to access gender-affirming care, only 45% support laws and policies banning the treatments for minors.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A June 2024 poll by the University of Chicago found that 70% of Democrats and 29% of Republicans supported laws that protect access to gender-affirming care for minors.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A poll by Folx Health in August 2024 found that 90% of transgender Americans feared that the election would have an impact on their access to gender-affirming care.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A September 2024 poll by Fox News found that voters trusted Kamala Harris more than Donald Trump to handle transgender issues by a 16-point margin.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An October 2024 poll by the Human Rights Campaign found that only 5% of voters say they are concerned about gender-affirming care and 61% said they will not support candidates who support banning gender-affirming care, including 41% of Republicans.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An October 2024 poll by Baldwin Wallace University in Ohio found that 60% of registered voters in Ohio supported schools teaching 6th-12th grade students about sexual orientation but only 43% supported teaching students in those same grades about gender identity.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Additionally, the poll found that 51% of voters in Ohio believe parents should not have direct control over what books are in the school library and 55% believe that parents should not be able to stop schools from teaching topics that they do not like.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In November 2024, polls in five battleground states conducted by *The New York Times*/Siena College found a majority of Americans think society should accept transgender people's gender identities.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In January 2025, a poll by *The New York Times*/Ipsos showed 71% of Americans believed that no trans person under 18 should have access to gender-affirming care and 79% of respondents supported a ban on transgender athletes from women's sports.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Additionally, 49% said that society had gone too far in accommodating the rights of trans people.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A February 2025 Gallup Poll found that 58% of Americans supported allowing openly transgender people to serve in the military, which was a decrease from 2021 when 66% of Americans supported it.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The decrease was largely caused by a massive decrease in support among Republicans.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Support among Democrats and Independents between 2021 and 2025 remained mostly steady.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A March 2025 survey by Public Religion Research Institute/Ipsos found that 70% of Democrats and 30% of Republicans opposed legislation that would ban minors from accessing gender-affirming care.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Additionally, 60% of Democrats and 14% of Republicans opposed legislation that would mandate that a transgender person's driver's license or ID match their sex at birth.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An April 2025 poll by 19th News/SurveyMonkey found that 49% of Americans do not want politicians focusing on transgender issues, a rise from 43% in 2024 and 44% in 2023.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The poll also found that 59% of Americans support transgender adults being able to access gender-affirming care.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] And while only 43% supported trans youth being able to access gender-affirming care, 55% opposed laws that would restrict gender-affirming care for minors.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An April 2025 survey by CNN/SSRS found that 51% of Americans, including 16% of Democrats/Liberals, 48% of Independents/Moderates and 90% of Republicans, but only 79% of Conservatives, approved of Donald Trump's handling of transgender issues.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A January 2026 YouGov poll found that 64% of Americans believe transphobia is a problem among members of the Republican Party, with 44% citing it as a major problem.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Notably, around 60% of respondents said they believe "trans ideology" and "gender ideology" were also issues, though the survey did not offer a definition of those terms.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] During the 2024 presidential election, anti-trans advertisements became commonplace, with the Republican Party making trans issues a top issue in their campaign, spending over $215 million on anti-trans ads and more than on ads regarding housing, immigration, and the economy combined.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] According to NOTUS in 2025, it was the American Principles Project who had originally convinced the Donald Trump and the Republican Party to begin its extensive campaign against trans rights.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, Democrats largely avoided discussing transgender issues during the election campaign period.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The ads became especially common during the closing days of the race, often pushing disparaging claims about transgender healthcare, existence in society, and participation in sports.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Democrats did not formally respond to the ads during the campaign period.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Former President Bill Clinton privately expressed concern about the ads and encouraged the Harris campaign to respond to it.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] However, he was told by the campaign that the ads "were not necessarily having an impact" and never addressed his concerns publicly.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The Harris campaign had originally planned to release an ad responding, but the ad ended up performing poorly in internal tests and was ultimately never run.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] According to an analysis by Future Forward, the political slogan "Kamala is for they/them, President Trump is for you" was ranked as one of the Trump campaign's most effective 30-second attack ads, shifting the race 2.7 percentage points in favor of Trump after viewers watched it.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On the contrary, an analysis by Change Research studying the effects of the ads found that they did not sway swing voters.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A study by Ground Media also found that the ads did not sway voters into supporting Republicans, but they did succeed at slightly eroding public support for trans people in general.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] David Rochkind, the CEO of Ground Media, gave a press release saying "What this demonstrates is that attacking the trans community isn't just a weak and feckless political strategy — it's a deeply cynical one. ...
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] These ads weaponize trans-identity to sow fear and division, making our country less safe for everyone." A poll by Blueprint surveyed the most important issues to voters and found that trans issues ranked second to last among young men.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An October 2024 poll by Data for Progress found that a majority of voters from both major parties believe the government should stop involving themselves in the lives of trans people and that politicians should focus less on transgender issues and more on other issues like the economy.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] It also found that a majority of voters from both major parties believe Republicans leaning so heavily on anti-trans ads is "sad and shameful".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An October 2024 Gallup Poll surveying the most important issues to registered voters ahead of the 2024 presidential election found that of the 22 issues voters were asked about, transgender issues ranked last with only 18 percent of voters describing it as "extremely important".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Democrats were also more likely than Republicans to say transgender issues were extremely important to them, 25% to 12%.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The poll showed that voter's discontent with the Biden administration, the economy and immigration were the main factors that led to Trump's victory.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Vox Media said that anti-trans ads have "no impact on whether people are likely to vote" and compared them to the "rising tide of fascism in the United States".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Kelley Robinson, the president of the Human Rights Campaign, called the ads "desperate" and accused Republicans of focusing on "sowing fear and chaos" instead of talking about other issues like the economy.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] These ads led two Democratic politicians, Sherrod Brown and Colin Allred, to capitulate, ceding the issue at least partially to the Republican position.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] After Donald Trump won the 2024 election, two other Democrat politicians, Tom Suozzi and Seth Moulton, partially blamed their party's loss on their support for trans issues.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Other Democrat politicians and human rights organizations disputed these claims, arguing polls showed that trans issues were not important to most voters and that voters were instead mobilized to vote for Trump due to other issues like inflation and the economy.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Texas Democratic Party Chair, Gilberto Hinojosa also expressed anti-transgender sentiments following the 2024 election.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Hinojosa subsequently apologized for his comments and resigned from his position after receiving backlash from other Democrats and LGBTQ advocacy groups.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The Harris campaign's LGBTQ engagement director, Sam Alleman, urged voters not to blame trans people for Harris' loss in the election saying "Please do not blame trans issues or trans people for why we lost. ...
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] However, Blueprint's lead pollster, Evan Roth Smith, said in an interview that with the *Rolling Stone* that people were misunderstanding the poll, saying that other issues like the economy and immigration ranked as much bigger priorities to swing voters.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Smith clarified that "I don't even see [the poll as indicating transgender issues were the reason Democrats lost].
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] I know there's some people who look at the Blueprint data and see that.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] An NBC News exit poll for the 2024 election found that Kamala Harris garnered more support from LGBTQ voters than any other presidential candidate in history, with 86% of LGBTQ voters backing Harris and 12% backing Donald Trump - a margin 15% larger than Joe Biden's margin over Trump in 2020.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In March 2025, Trump indicated that attacking trans rights would be a large part of Republicans' main talking points in the 2026 midterm elections, saying that he had told Republicans, "Don't bring that subject up, because there's no election right now.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Democratic strategist Matt Angle suggested that in 2026, Democrats should adopt a strategy of showing voters that Republicans are exploiting transgender issues to cover up their failures on other issues like healthcare.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Beginning in 2025, gay rights, specifically gay marriage, increasingly became under attack by Republican politicians and state legislatures.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] By February 2025, nine states had introduced legislation intended to chip away at gay marriage.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Five of the measures introduced in Michigan, Idaho, Montana, North Dakota and South Dakota specifically urged the Supreme Court to overturn its 2015 ruling, *Obergefell v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Hodges*, which legalized gay marriage nationwide.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The other four introduced in Missouri, Oklahoma, Tennessee and Texas would create a category for marriage called "covenant marriage" that would be only for one man and one woman.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In November 2025, the Supreme Court weighed whether to revisit the *Obergefell* ruling when they considered whether to hear an appeal to *Ermold v.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Davis* brought by Kim Davis, a Kentucky court clerk who refused to issue marriage licenses to same-sex couples following Obergefell ruling in 2015.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The appeal specifically asked the court to overturn Obergefell.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The Supreme Court declined the appeal on November 10.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In early 2026, The Heritage Foundation, the right-wing group responsible for Project 2025, released a report opposing gay marriage.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Scholars have argued that the media has contributed to increasing marginalization of LGBTQ+ people, especially in its coverage of trans people.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2015, anti-trans media coverage has increasingly focused on trans youth and trans athletes.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] *Teen Vogue* news and politics editor Lexi McMenamin said publications such as *The New York Times*, *The Atlantic*, the *Washington Post*, and *The Guardian* had published articles with an anti-trans bias.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Elischberger suggests that the U.S. should implement media policy reforms to protect trans people from disinformation.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2022, *The New York Times*' reporting on transgender issues was criticized by the World Professional Association for Transgender Health, especially in regards to treatments for trans children.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] On February 15, 2023, two open letters were published, accusing the *Times* of publishing biased and misleading articles about trans people.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] These were signed by almost 1,200 past and current contributors, tens of thousands of readers and subscribers, and over 100 LGBTQ and civil rights groups—including GLAAD, the Human Rights Campaign and PFLAG.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The letters said the paper had published articles biased against transgender, non⁠-⁠binary, and gender nonconforming people, including "fringe theories", "dangerous inaccuracies", "pseudoscience" and "euphemistic, charged language".
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The letters also noted that the coverage was cited in an amicus brief in support of an anti-trans law in Alabama.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Some trans people and their families have fled to other US states or countries, including the families of those who actively advocated against anti-trans laws in their states.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Many families cite increasing social pressure and restrictions on gender-affirming care as reasons for moving.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A 2023 poll by Data for Progress found that 8 percent of transgender adults and 8 percent of LGBTQ 18-to-24-year-olds had moved out of their state as a result of anti-LGBTQ legislation.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] A 2025 report by The Trevor Project estimates 266,000 young people and their family members had moved to other states because of anti-LGBTQ policies.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Several states passed legislation preventing trans people and their families, as well as their healthcare providers relocating from other states, from being extradited.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2022, Connecticut became the first state to implement such a law, alongside similar protections for reproductive healthcare providers and recipients.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Massachusetts, California, Illinois, Minnesota, New Jersey, Maryland, and Washington, D.C. have passed similar laws.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Some trans Americans have considered claiming asylum in other countries, including European countries or Canada.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] However, some political analysts note that asylum applications will likely be denied, as no federal law exists restricting LGBTQ safety and because transgender individuals can likely move to a safer state in their own country.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Others worry that potential asylum applications could overwhelm immigration systems and prevent asylum access for those from more dangerous territory.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] The increased targeting of LGBTQ people by right-wing militia groups such as the Proud Boys and the Oath Keepers has led some LGBTQ people, particularly in conservative states such as Texas, to stockpile and train to use weapons and gear, including AR-15 rifles and modern body armor.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In May 2023, the Human Rights Campaign issued a travel advisory for the state of Florida, citing new laws targeting the LGBTQ community.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] After a ten-day tour in which he met with State officials in Alabama, Florida, and California in August 2022, Victor Madrigal-Borloz, a United Nations Independent Expert on protection against violence and discrimination, warned about the erosion of LGBTQ rights in the United States.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] Madrigal-Borloz stated: "I am deeply alarmed by a widespread, profoundly negative riptide created by deliberate actions to roll back the human rights of LGBT people at state level.
[src:breast-binding/2020s-anti-lgbtq-movement-in-the-united-states-p02] In August 2023, the Government of Canada issued a travel warning for LGBTQ visitors to the United States, advising citizens to check their destination's local laws before traveling.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:breast-binding/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] This treatment is regarded as a form of violence against women and a violation of women's rights.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] It is a recurring issue in facilities around the globe, according to World Health Organization studies, and can have serious consequences for mother and child.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Namely, abuse during childbirth may prevent women from seeking pre-natal care and using other health care services in the future.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Adolescents, unmarried women, women of low socioeconomic status, migrant women, women infected with HIV, and ethnic minority women are at a greater risk of experiencing obstetric violence.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The World Health Organization notes that abuse during childbirth has yet to be conclusively defined or measured scientifically.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] However, abuse during childbirth is generally defined as neglectful, physical abusive, and/or disrespectful treatment from healthcare professionals towards patients in childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Such mistreatment is regarded as a violation of the woman's human rights.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Abuse during childbirth can occur over a wide spectrum and may be seen in the forms of non-confidential care, non-dignified care, discrimination, overt physical abuse, non-consented care, abandonment of care, and/or detention in facilities.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Investigations into the prevalence of abusive practices in childbirth have been conducted by the World Health Organization.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Their studies demonstrate that women giving birth in medical facilities experience disrespectful, abusive, and/or neglectful treatment frequently and globally.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] A 2020 study centered in Ghana, Guinea, Myanmar, and Nigeria found that more than 40% of observed women and 35% of surveyed women experienced mistreatment while in childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Furthermore, adolescents, migrant women, women infected with HIV, and ethnic minority women were deemed more likely than others to experience abuse during childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Several systemic and sociocultural barriers continue to place women at a disadvantage in society.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] These include antiquated gender roles that cause physicians and others to view women as weak or vulnerable.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Women in childbirth are very vulnerable and often cannot protect themselves against mistreatment, so the consequences of obstetric violence can be serious for both the mother and the child.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] It is often difficult to escape the gender bias in healthcare, which causes women to feel unsafe when considering asking for help or ways to protect themselves.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The abusive relationship that forms between a woman and her healthcare providers as a result of abuse during childbirth often leads to the woman developing a general mistrust of healthcare services.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Furthermore, consequences can be extended to include a reluctance to seek pre-natal care, medical assistance during childbirth, and other health care services in the future.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Some sources refer to North American obstetricians and gynecologists, especially between the 1950s and 1980s, practicing what was called the *husband's stitch*, which involves placing extra stitches in the woman's vagina after the episiotomy or the natural tearing that occurs during childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] This procedure was supposedly performed to increase the husband's future sexual pleasure and often caused long-term pain and discomfort for the woman.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] There is no proof that such a practice was widespread in North America, but mentions of it frequently appear in studies about episiotomy in certain American countries such as Brazil.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] There has been a more recent highlight on North American doctors' treatment of pregnant women.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The growing idea is that there has been a "redressing" of obstetric violence and that women's right to choice has been compromised in some situations.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] In instances where the lives of the woman and the fetus are endangered, the woman has the right to refuse care through procedures such as caesarean section, episiotomy, or vacuum-assisted delivery.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Women are often coerced into having these invasive procedures, even though such coercion has been found to cause long-lasting damage, with many women comparing the experience to rape.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The term "obstetric violence" is particularly used in Latin American countries, where the law prohibits such mistreatment.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] These laws exist in several Latin American countries, including Argentina, Puerto Rico and Venezuela.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Research into obstetric violence at two public hospitals in Mexico, analyzing the birthing experiences for one month of 2012, found that physical abuse, verbal abuse, and discrimination occurred openly throughout the facilities.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Women receiving government-assisted insurance were subjected to the most discrimination from the healthcare professionals.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Tanzania is an African country with a history of abuse during childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] In 2011, Shannon McMahon and others explored whether or not the supposed interventions to decrease the prevalence of abuse during childbirth had been effective.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] When interviewing women, they initially referred to their experiences as neutral or better.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] However, after being shown the different aspects of abuse, an overwhelming majority of the women actually reported experiencing abuse during childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] In 2013–2014, Hannah Ratcliffe and others formed a study to explore possible interventions to improve the experiences of women in childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] They implemented an "open birth day" that facilitated communication between patients and providers and educated them on the procedures surrounding birth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The team also implemented a "respectful maternity care workshop" meant to create conversation surrounding respect between health care staff and patients.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] What they found was that this approach was successful in helping reconstruct systems without costing much.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] There was an increase of 60% in satisfaction with women's delivery experience.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] During the same time period as Ratcliffe's study, Stephanie Kujawaki and others did a comparative study of births with and without interventions.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The baseline for the study was conducted in 2011–2012, and the final half of the study was conducted in 2015.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] What they found is that there was a 66% reduction in abuse and disrespect during childbirth after interventions.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] This study shows that community and health system reforms can help change and reshape norms in which women are mistreated during childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] In 2014–2015, Shreeporna Bhattacharya and T.K.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Sundari Ravindran set out to quantitatively determine the prevalence of abuse during childbirth in the Varanasi district of northern India through the use of a questionnaire.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Two rural blocks in the Varanasi district with high rates of institutional deliveries were the focus of the study, with subjects selected randomly from the women who lived in the area.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Bhattacharya and Ravindran report that the frequency at which abusive behavior occurred was 28.8%, with "abusive behavior" acting as a general term.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The two most common forms of abuse were non-dignified care (19.3%) and physical abuse (13.4%).
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Furthermore, 8.5% of patients reported being neglected or abandoned, 5.6% experienced non-confidential care, and 4.9% faced humiliation due to a lack of cleanliness.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The authors also note that 90.5% of subjects were met with inappropriate demands for money.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] In terms of correlation, there was no significant link between socio-economic status and abuse, though women who faced complications during labor were four times as likely to experience abuse in the facilities.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Fatima Alzyoud and colleagues studied abuse during childbirth in Jordan, specifically in the forms of neglect and verbal abuse.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Four government-run Maternal and Child Health Centers were used as the locations of the study, with the subjects being 390 Jordanian women aged 18–45.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The Childbirth Verbal Abuse and Neglect Scale (CVANS) found that 32.2% of the subjects experienced neglect and 37.7% faced verbal abuse during their last childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Furthermore, there was a negative correlation between age and neglect/verbal abuse.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] While global maternal health research and advocacy have brought recent awareness to obstetric violence, historians have noted historical examples.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] In the United States of America, historians attest that it began during slavery, where enslaved women were physically exploited and experimented on by Antebellum physicians looking to advance the fields of obstetrics and gynaecology.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Later, historians confirm that this took the form of forced sterilizations of black and other women of color as part of the eugenics movement.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Mississippi appendectomies refer to the experience of forced and coerced sterilization of Black women between 1920 and 1980.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Coined by activist Fannie Lou Hamer, Mississippi appendectomies involved Black and other women of color being sterilized without informed consent, knowledge, and without a valid medical reason.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Hamer recalls having received a hysterectomy, without consent, during a surgery to remove a uterine fibroid, rendering her infertile.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Researchers confirm that hysterectomies and tubal ligations were given to poor black women by medical residents allowed to "practice" surgical skills.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Scholars show that some of these historical forms of disrespectful care have persisted into the 21st century.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The study concluded that Black mothers and infants were two times as likely to die as white mothers and infants within this tax bracket.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] The researchers also found that the rates of maternal mortality among the richest Black women were just as high among the lowest-income white women.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Another study noted that women of color experience mistreatment more frequently than other races, with rates of mistreatment consistently higher for them when compared to white counterparts.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] Though studies have found that the impacts of obstetric violence are disproportionately distributed, they also show it is not limited to black women alone.
[src:breast-binding/abuse-during-childbirth] A study conducted during the 1970s found that an estimated one-quarter of Indigenous American women of childbearing age were sterilized in Indian Health Service hospitals.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Since the launch of the site in 2008, the number of users has grown rapidly, reaching about 10 million daily visits in early 2022.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] By 2024, Academia.edu has over 270 million registered users, with over 55 million papers currently available on the platform.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] In 2022, the company entered the scientific publishing sector, launching a dozen scientific, open access journals, and publishing under the name of Academia.edu Journals.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Academia.edu was founded by Richard Price in 2008.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] On its filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the company uses the legal name Academia Inc.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] The site was registered in the .edu top-level domain in 1999 when that domain was not limited to educational institutions.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] In 2013, Elsevier sent thousands of takedown notices to Academia.edu, claiming copyright infringement for Elsevier-published content that was posted on Academia.edu.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Following widespread complaint of these takedown notices, Elsevier retracted their request, and academics were allowed to continue to post their publications.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Critics mention several alternatives for free access publications for people who want to make their work freely available.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Many universities and educational consortia have their own institutional repositories, including the Big Ten Academic Alliance.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Zenodo (funded by The OpenAIRE Consortium) and Humanities Commons both work to keep humanities scholarship online without monetizing it.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Academia.edu's competitors include ResearchGate, Google Scholar and Mendeley.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] In 2016 Academia.edu reportedly had more registered users than ResearchGate (about 34 million versus 11 million) and higher web traffic, but ResearchGate had substantially more active usage by researchers.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] In 2020, the traffic ranks had reversed, with ResearchGate ranked in the top 150–200 websites globally according to Alexa Internet, whereas Academia.edu was positioned in the 200–300 range.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Unpaywall, which collects data about open access versions of academic publications and provides easy access to them, is also considered a competitor to Academia.edu.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] As of December 2025, Academia.edu Journals has launched 18 open-access journals that publish articles in various scientific fields, including medicine.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] As a gold open-access publisher, all articles are freely available.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] All journals waived article processing charges for authors during the year in which the journal was launched, and continue to waive these fees for authors who come from eligible countries or can prove difficulty with paying due to lack of funding.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Academia.edu is not a university or institution for higher learning and so under current standards it would not qualify for the ".edu" top-level domain.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] However, since the domain name "Academia.edu" was registered in 1999, before the regulations required .edu domain names to be held solely by accredited post-secondary institutions in the US, it is allowed to remain active and operational.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] All .edu domain names registered before 2001 were grandfathered in, even if not an accredited USA post-secondary institution.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Academia.edu claims it supports the open science or open access movements and, in particular, instant distribution of research, and a peer-review system that occurs alongside distribution, instead of before it.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Accordingly, the company stated its opposition to the proposed (since withdrawn) 2011 U.S.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Research Works Act, which would have prevented open-access mandates in the U.S.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] However, in the view of critic Peter Suber, Academia.edu is not an open access repository and is not recommended as a way to pursue green open access.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Peter Suber instead invites researchers to use field-specific repositories or general-purpose repositories like Zenodo.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] In early 2016, some users reported having received e-mails from Academia.edu where they were asked if they would be interested in paying a fee to have their papers recommended by the website's editors.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] This led some users to start a campaign encouraging users to cancel their Academia.edu accounts.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] Other criticisms include the fact that Academia.edu uses a vendor lock-in model: "It's up to Academia.edu to decide what you can and can't do with the information you've given them, and they're not likely to make it easy for alternative methods to access".
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] This is in reference to the fact that, although papers can be read by non-users, a free account is needed in order to download papers: "you need to be logged in to do most of the useful things on the site (even as a casual reader)".
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] In December 2016, Academia.edu announced new premium features that includes data analytics on work and the professional rank of the viewers, which have also received criticism.
[src:breast-binding/academia-edu] This strategy, where key financial terms are presented in visually muted text with low contrast, is viewed as a violation of transaction transparency principles and consumer protection standards.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] The **Act to Protect against Conversion Treatments** (German: *Gesetz zum Schutz vor Konversionsbehandlungen*) is a German federal law.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] It prohibits the use of conversion therapy (called *conversion treatment* in the Act) on minors and adults who have not given their effective consent, and makes it a criminal offence.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] Conversion treatments are defined as treatments "aimed at changing or suppressing sexual orientation or self-perceived gender identity", but not the treatment of "medically recognised disorders of sexual preference" or surgical and hormonal gender-affirming measures.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] Public advertising, offering and brokering conversion therapies is punishable as an administrative offence.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] Brokering conversion therapy for a minor is generally punishable as aiding and abetting the performance of the treatment in accordance with § 27 German Criminal Code in conjunction with § 5 of this Act if the brokered conversion therapy was performed.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] The World Health Organisation (WHO) has declared that both homosexuality and transgender identity are not mental disorders, and that there is no indication for therapy.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] Since 1991, homosexuality has no longer been listed as a mental disorder in the ICD-10, and "transsexualism" was removed from the chapter on mental disorders when the ICD-11 came into force in 2022.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] In 2013, the World Medical Association condemned conversion therapy as a violation of human rights that is incompatible with medical ethics.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] The following year, the German Medical Assembly of the German Medical Association issued a warning about its negative health effects.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] The Act requires the Federal Institute of Public Health (BIÖG) to offer free and anonymous counselling.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] This is to be provided as a telephone and online counselling service for people affected by conversion therapy or their relatives, as well as for people in general who are dealing with issues of sexual orientation and gender identity.
[src:breast-binding/act-to-protect-against-conversion-treatments-germany] It is provided via the website Liebesleben.de (see External links).
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The definition of teenage pregnancy includes those who are legally considered adults in their country.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The World Health Organization defines *adolescence* as the period between the ages of 10 and 19 years.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Pregnancy can occur with sexual intercourse after the start of ovulation, which can happen before the first menstrual period (*menarche*).
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In healthy, well-nourished girls, the first period usually takes place between the ages of 12 and 13.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Pregnant teenagers face many of the same pregnancy-related issues as older women.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenagers are more likely to experience pregnancy complications or maternal death than women older than 19.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] There are additional concerns for those under the age of 15 as they are less likely to be physically developed to sustain a healthy pregnancy or to give birth.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] For girls aged 15–19, risks are associated more with socioeconomic factors than with the biological effects of age.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Risks of low birth weight, premature labor, anemia, and pre-eclampsia are not connected to biological age by the time a girl is aged 16, as they are not observed in births to older teens after controlling for other risk factors, such as access to high-quality prenatal care.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage pregnancies are related to social issues, including lower educational levels and poverty.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage pregnancy in developed countries is usually outside of marriage and is often associated with a social stigma.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage pregnancy in developing countries often occurs within marriage and approximately half are planned.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] However, in these societies, early pregnancy may combine with malnutrition and poor health care to cause medical problems.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] When used in combination, educational interventions and access to birth control can reduce unintended teenage pregnancies.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2023, globally, about 41 females per 1,000 gave birth between the ages of 15 and 19, compared with roughly 65 births per 1,000 in 2000.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] From 2015 to 2021, an estimated 14 percent of adolescent girls and young women globally reported giving birth before age 18.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The adolescent birth rate is higher in lower- and middle-income countries (LMIC), compared to higher- income countries.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the developing world, approximately 2.5 million females aged 15 to 19 years old have children each year.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] It is more common in rural than urban areas.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2021, 13.3 million babies, or about 10 percent of the total worldwide, were born to mothers under 20 years old.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The World Health Organization defines adolescence as the period between the ages of 10 and 19 years.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The mother's age is determined by the easily verified date when the pregnancy *ends*, not by the estimated date of conception.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Consequently, the statistics do not include pregnancies that began at age 19, but that ended on or after the woman's 20th birthday.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Similarly, statistics on the mother's marital status are determined by whether she is married at the end of the pregnancy, not at the time of conception.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage pregnancy, with conceptions normally involving girls between ages 16 and 19, was far more normal in previous centuries, and common in developed countries in the 20th century.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Among Norwegian women born in the early 1950s, nearly a quarter became teenage mothers by the early 1970s.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The rates have steadily declined throughout the developed world since that 20th-century peak.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Among those born in Norway in the late 1970s, less than 10% became teenage mothers, and rates have fallen since then.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] According to the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), "Pregnancies among girls less than 18 years of age have irreparable consequences.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The risk of maternal death for girls under age 15 in low and middle-income countries is higher than for women in their twenties.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage pregnancy also affects girls' education and income potential, as many are forced to drop out of school, which ultimately threatens future opportunities and economic prospects.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Studies have examined the socioeconomic, medical, and psychological impact of pregnancy and parenthood in teens.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Life outcomes for teenage mothers and their children vary.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Other factors, such as poverty or social support, may be more important than the age of the mother at the birth.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Many solutions to counteract the more negative findings have been proposed.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage parents who can rely on family and community support, social services, and child-care support are more likely to continue their education and get higher-paying jobs as they progress with their education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A holistic approach is required to address teenage pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] This means not focusing on changing the behaviour of girls but addressing the underlying reasons of adolescent pregnancy, such as poverty, gender inequality, social pressures, and coercion.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the United States, one-third of high school students reported being sexually active.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2011–2013, 79% of females reported using birth control.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage pregnancy puts young women at risk for health issues, as well as economic, social, and financial issues.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Being a young mother in a first-world country can affect one's education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teen mothers are more likely to drop out of high school.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2001 study found that women who gave birth during their teens completed secondary-level schooling 10–12% as often and pursued post-secondary education 14–29% as often as women who waited until age 30.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] According to the National Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy, nearly 1 in 4 teen mothers will experience another pregnancy within two years of having their first.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Pregnancy and giving birth significantly increases the chance that these mothers will become high school dropouts, and as many as half have to go on welfare.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Many teen parents do not have the intellectual or emotional maturity that is needed to provide for another life.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Often, these pregnancies are hidden for months, resulting in a lack of adequate prenatal care and dangerous outcomes for the babies.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Factors that determine which mothers are more likely to have closely spaced repeat births include marriage and education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The likelihood decreases with the level of education of the young woman, or her parents, and increases if she gets married.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2019–2021 study of births in the United States found that girls who gave birth aged 10–13 and 18–19 had higher risks of cesarean delivery compared with girls aged 14–17.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Early motherhood can affect the psychosocial development of the infant.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The children of teen mothers are more likely to be born prematurely with a low birth weight, predisposing them to many other lifelong conditions.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Children of teen mothers are at higher risk of intellectual, language, and socio-emotional delays.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Developmental disabilities and behavioral issues are increased in children born to teen mothers.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] One study suggested that adolescent mothers are less likely to stimulate their infant through affectionate behaviors such as touch, smiling, and verbal communication, or to be sensitive and accepting toward their needs.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Another found that those who had more social support were less likely to show anger toward their children or to rely upon punishment.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Poor academic performance in the children of teenage mothers has also been noted, with many of the children being held back a grade level, scoring lower on standardized tests, and/or failing to graduate from secondary school.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Daughters born to adolescent parents are more likely to become teen mothers themselves.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Sons born to teenage mothers are three times more likely to serve time in prison.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Maternal and prenatal health is of particular concern among teens who are pregnant or parenting.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The worldwide incidence of premature birth and low birth weight is higher among adolescent mothers.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In a rural hospital in West Bengal, teenage mothers between 15 and 19 years old were more likely to have anemia, preterm delivery, and a baby with a lower birth weight than mothers between 20 and 24 years old.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Research indicates that pregnant teens are less likely to receive prenatal care, often seeking it in the third trimester, if at all.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The Guttmacher Institute reports that one-third of pregnant teens receive insufficient prenatal care and that their children are more likely to have health issues in childhood or be hospitalized than those born to older women.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the United States, teenage Latinas who become pregnant face barriers to receiving healthcare because they are the least insured group in the country.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Young mothers who are given high-quality maternity care have significantly healthier babies than those who are not.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Many of the health issues associated with teenage mothers appear to result from a lack of access to adequate medical care.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Many pregnant teens are at risk of nutritional deficiencies from poor eating habits common in adolescence, including attempts to lose weight through dieting, skipping meals, food faddism, snacking, and consumption of fast food.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Inadequate nutrition during pregnancy is an even more marked problem among teenagers in developing countries.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Complications of pregnancy result in the deaths of an estimated 70,000 teen girls in developing countries each year.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Young mothers and their babies are also at greater risk of contracting HIV.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The World Health Organization estimates that the risk of death following pregnancy is twice as high for girls aged 15–19 than for women aged 20–24.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The maternal mortality rate can be up to five times higher for girls aged 10–14 than for women aged 20–24.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Illegal abortion also holds many risks for teenage girls in areas such as sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Worldwide, pregnancy complications are the leading cause of death for women and girls 15 to 19 years old.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Risks for medical complications are greater for girls aged under 15, as an underdeveloped pelvis can lead to difficulties in childbirth.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Obstructed labour is normally dealt with by caesarean section in industrialized nations.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In developing regions where medical services might be unavailable, it can lead to eclampsia, obstetric fistula, infant mortality, or maternal death.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] For mothers who are older than fifteen, age is not a risk factor, and poor outcomes are associated more with socioeconomic factors rather than with biology.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The agency noted regional disparities, noting that in West and Central Africa, "48 percent of newborns to adolescent mothers had a postnatal contact as compared to 52 percent of newborns to all mothers".
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The lifetime opportunity cost caused by teenage pregnancy in different countries varies, from 1% to 30% of the annual GDP, with 30% being the figure in Uganda.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the United States, teenage pregnancy costs taxpayers between $9.4 and $28 billion in 2016, due to factors such as foster care and lost tax revenue.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2014 study estimated that an increase in economic productivity from ending teenage pregnancy in Brazil and India would be worth $3.5 billion and $7.7 billion respectively.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Less than one-third of teenage mothers receive any form of child support, vastly increasing the likelihood of turning to the government for assistance.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The correlation between earlier childbearing and failure to complete high school reduces career opportunities for many young women.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] One study found that, in 1988, 60% of teenage mothers were impoverished at the time of giving birth.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2002 study found that nearly 50% of all adolescent mothers sought social assistance within the first five years of their child's life.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 1999 study of 100 teenage mothers in the UK found that only 11% received a salary, while the remaining 89% were unemployed.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Most British teenage mothers live in poverty, with nearly half in the bottom fifth of the income distribution.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Rates of teenage pregnancies are higher in societies where it is traditional for girls to marry young and where they are encouraged to bear children as soon as they are able.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] For example, in some sub-Saharan African countries, early pregnancy is often seen as a blessing because it is proof of the young woman's fertility.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Countries where teenage marriages are common experience higher levels of teenage pregnancies.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the Indian subcontinent, early marriage and pregnancy are more common in traditional rural communities than in cities.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Many teenagers are not taught about methods of birth control and how to deal with peers who pressure them into having sex before they are ready.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Many pregnant teenagers do not have any knowledge of the central facts of sexuality.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Economic incentives also influences the decision to have children.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In societies where children are set to work at an early age, it is economically attractive to have many children.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Most teenage pregnancies in the developed world appear to be unplanned.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Many Western countries have instituted sex education programs, the main objective of which is to reduce unplanned pregnancies and STIs.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Countries with low levels of teenagers giving birth accept sexual relationships among teenagers and provide comprehensive and balanced information about sexuality.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage pregnancies are common among Romani people because they marry earlier.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teen pregnancy and motherhood can influence younger siblings.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] One study found that the younger sisters of teen mothers were less likely to emphasize the importance of education and employment and more likely to accept human sexual behavior, parenting, and marriage at younger ages.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Younger brothers, too, were found to be more tolerant of non-marital and early births, in addition to being more susceptible to high-risk behaviors.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] If the younger sisters of teenage parents babysit the children, they have an increased probability of getting pregnant themselves.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Once an older daughter has a child, parents often become more accepting as time goes by.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2011 study in Norway found that the probability of a younger sister having a teenage pregnancy went from 1:5 to 2:5 if the elder sister had a baby as a teenager.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In most countries, most males experience sexual intercourse for the first time before their 20th birthday.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Males in Western developed countries have sex for the first time sooner than in undeveloped and culturally conservative countries such as sub-Saharan Africa and much of Asia.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In a 2005 Kaiser Family Foundation study of US teenagers, 29% of teens reported feeling pressure to have sex, 33% of sexually active teens reported "being in a relationship where they felt things were moving too fast sexually", and 24% had "done something sexual they didn't really want to do".
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Several polls have indicated peer pressure as a factor in encouraging both girls and boys to have sex.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The increased sexual activity among adolescents is manifested in increased teenage pregnancies and an increase in sexually transmitted diseases.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Inhibition-reducing drugs and alcohol may encourage unintended sexual activity.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] If so, it is unknown if the drugs themselves directly influence teenagers to engage in riskier behavior, or whether teenagers who engage in drug use are more likely to engage in sex.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The drugs with the strongest evidence linking them to teenage pregnancy are alcohol, cannabis, "ecstasy" and other substituted amphetamines.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Girls who mature early (precocious puberty) are more likely to engage in sexual intercourse at a younger age, which in turn puts them at greater risk of teenage pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Adolescents may lack knowledge of, or access to, conventional methods of preventing pregnancy, as they may be too embarrassed or frightened to seek such information.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Contraception for teenagers presents a huge challenge for the clinician.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 1998, the government of the UK set a target to halve the under-18 pregnancy rate by 2010.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The Teenage Pregnancy Strategy (TPS) was established to achieve this.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The pregnancy rate in this group, although falling, rose slightly in 2007, to 41.7 per 1,000 women.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Young women often think of contraception either as 'the pill' or condoms, and have little knowledge about other methods.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] They are heavily influenced by negative, second-hand stories about methods of contraception from their friends and the media.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Prejudices are extremely difficult to overcome.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Over concern about side-effects, for example weight gain and acne, often affects choice.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Missing up to three pills a month is common, and in this age group, the figure is likely to be higher.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Restarting after the pill-free week, having to hide pills, drug interactions, and difficulty getting repeat prescriptions can all lead to method failure.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the US, according to the 2002 National Survey of Family Growth, sexually active adolescent women wishing to avoid pregnancy were less likely than older women to use contraceptives (18% of 15–19-year-olds used no contraceptives, versus 10.7% for women aged 15–44).
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] More than 80% of teen pregnancies are unintended.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Over half of unintended pregnancies were to women not using contraceptives, most of the rest are due to inconsistent or incorrect use.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] 23% of sexually active young women in a 1996 *Seventeen* magazine poll admitted to having had unprotected sex with a partner who did not use a condom, while 70% of girls in a 1997 *PARADE* poll claimed it was embarrassing to buy birth control or request information from a doctor.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 1995, the National Longitudinal Study of Adolescent Health surveyed 1,027 students in the US in grades 7–12 to compare the use of contraceptives among Whites, Blacks, and Hispanics.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] 36.2% of Hispanics said they never used contraception during intercourse, compared to 23.3% of Black teens and 17.0% of White teens who did not use contraceptives during intercourse.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In a 2012 US study, over 1,000 females were surveyed to find out the factors contributing to not using contraception.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Of those surveyed, almost half had been involved in unprotected sex within the previous three months.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] These women gave three main reasons for not using contraceptives: trouble obtaining birth control (the most frequent reason), lack of intention to have sex, and the misconception that they "could not get pregnant".
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In a 2011 study for the Guttmacher Institute, researchers found that, from a comparative perspective, however, teenage pregnancy rates in the US are less nuanced than one might initially assume.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Among teens in the UK seeking an abortion, a 2007 study found that the rate of contraceptive use was roughly the same for teens as for older women.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In other cases, contraception is used, but proves to be inadequate.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Inexperienced adolescents may use condoms incorrectly, forget to take oral contraceptives, or fail to use the contraceptives they had previously chosen.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Contraceptive failure rates are higher for teenagers, particularly poor ones, than for older users.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] According to *Encyclopedia of Women's Health*, published in 2004, there has been an increased effort to provide contraception to adolescents via family planning services and school-based health, such as HIV prevention education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2025 study, using Swedish data, found that the introduction of the birth control pill could explain half of the decline in teenage pregnancy following its introduction.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Studies from South Africa have found that 11–20% of pregnancies in teenagers are a direct result of rape.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] About 60% of teenage mothers had unwanted sexual experiences preceding their pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Before age 15, a majority of first-intercourse experiences among females are reported to be non-voluntary.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The Guttmacher Institute found that 60% of girls who had sex before age 15 were coerced by males, who, on average, were six years their senior.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2003, one in five teenage fathers admitted to forcing girls to have sex with them.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Multiple studies have indicated a strong link between early childhood sexual abuse and subsequent teenage pregnancy in industrialized countries.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Up to 70% of women who gave birth in their teens were molested as young girls.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] By contrast, 25% of women who did not give birth as teens were molested.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In some countries, sexual intercourse between a minor and an adult is not considered consensual under the law because a minor is believed to lack the maturity and competence to make an informed decision to engage in fully consensual sex with an adult.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In those countries, sex with a minor is therefore considered statutory rape.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Therefore, the definition of statutory rape is limited to sex with a person under the minimum age of consent.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] What constitutes statutory rape ultimately differs by jurisdiction (see age of consent).
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Studies have indicated that adolescent girls are often in abusive relationships at the time of their conception.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] They have also reported that knowledge of their pregnancy has often intensified violent and controlling behaviors on part of their boyfriends.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Girls under age 18 are twice as likely to be beaten by their child's father as women over age 18.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A UK study found that 70% of women who gave birth in their teens had experienced adolescent domestic violence.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Similar results have been found in studies in the US.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A Washington State study found 70% of teenage mothers had been beaten by their boyfriends, 51% had experienced attempts of birth control sabotage within the last year, and 21% experienced school or work sabotage.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In a study of 379 pregnant or parenting teens and 95 teenage girls without children, 62% of girls aged 11–15 and 56% of girls aged 16–19 reported experiencing domestic violence at the hands of their partners.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Moreover, 51% of the girls reported experiencing at least one instance where their boyfriend attempted to sabotage their efforts to use birth control.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage pregnancy has been defined predominantly within the research field and among social agencies as a social problem.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Poverty is associated with increased rates of teenage pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Economically poor countries such as Niger and Bangladesh have far more teenage mothers compared with economically rich countries such as Switzerland and Japan.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the UK in 2001, around half of all pregnancies to those under 18 were concentrated among the 30% most deprived population, with only 14% occurring among the 30% least deprived.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] For example, in Italy in 2001, the teenage birth rate in the well-off central regions is only 3.3 per 1,000, while in the poorer Mezzogiorno it is 10.0 per 1,000.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Similarly, in the US in 2001, sociologist Mike A.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teen pregnancy costs the US over $9.1 billion in 2004, including $1.9 billion for health care, $2.3 billion for child welfare, $2.1 billion for incarceration, and $2.9 billion in lower tax revenue.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] There is little evidence to support the common belief that teenage mothers become pregnant to get benefits, welfare, and council housing.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Most knew little about housing or financial aid before they got pregnant, and what they thought they knew often turned out to be wrong.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Girls exposed to abuse, domestic violence, and family strife in childhood are more likely to become pregnant as teenagers, and the risk of becoming pregnant as a teenager increases with the number of adverse childhood experiences.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In a 2004 study, one-third of teenage pregnancies could be prevented by eliminating exposure to abuse, violence, and family strife.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2001 study suggested that boys raised by mothers who experienced physical abuse, or who experienced domestic violence directly, were more likely to be involved in a teenage pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2003 study found that girls whose fathers left the family early in their lives had the highest rates of early sexual activity and adolescent pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Girls whose fathers left them at a later age had a lower rate of early sexual activity.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The lowest rates are found in girls whose fathers were present throughout their childhood.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Low educational expectations have been pinpointed as a risk factor.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A girl is more likely to become a teenage parent if her mother or older sister gave birth in her teens.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A majority of respondents in a 1988 Joint Center for Political and Economic Studies survey attributed the occurrence of adolescent pregnancy to a breakdown of communication between parents and child and also to inadequate parental supervision.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Foster care youth are more likely than their peers to become pregnant as teenagers.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The National Casey Alumni Study, which surveyed foster care alumni from 23 communities across the US, found the birth rate for girls in foster care was more than double the rate of their peers outside the foster care system.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A University of Chicago study of youth transitioning out of foster care in Illinois, Iowa, and Wisconsin found that nearly half of the females had been pregnant by age 19.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The Utah Department of Human Services found that girls who had left the foster care system between 1999 and 2004 had a birth rate nearly three times the rate for girls in the general population.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2006 study found that adolescents who were more exposed to sexuality in the media were more likely to engage in sexual activity themselves.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] According to *Time*, "teens exposed to the most sexual content on TV are twice as likely as teens watching less of this material to become pregnant before they reach age 20".
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Comprehensive sex education and access to birth control appear to reduce unplanned teenage pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] It is unclear which type of intervention is most effective.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the US free access to a long acting form of reversible birth control along with education decreased the rates of teen pregnancies by around 80% and the rate of abortions by more than 75%.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Currently there are four federal programs aimed at preventing teenage pregnancy: Teen Pregnancy Prevention (TPP), Personal Responsibility Education Program (PREP), Title V Sexual Risk Avoidance Education, and Sexual Risk Avoidance Education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The Dutch approach to preventing teenage pregnancy has often been seen as a model by other countries.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The curriculum focuses on values, attitudes, communication, and negotiation skills, as well as biological aspects of reproduction.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The media has encouraged open dialogue, and the health-care system guarantees confidentiality and a non-judgmental approach.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the United States in 2016, 39 states and the District of Columbia out of the 50 states required some form of sex education and/or HIV education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Out of these 39 states and the District of Columbia, 17 states require that the sexual education provided be medically accurate, and 3 states prohibit a program from promoting sexual education in a religious way.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] These three states include California, Colorado, and Louisiana.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] 19 of those 39 states stress the importance of only having sex when in a committed marriage.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] From this data, 11 states currently have no requirement for sexual education for any years of schooling, meaning these 11 states may have no sexual education at all.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] This could mean these states are allowed to teach sexual education in any way they would like, including in medically inaccurate ways.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] This point is also valid for those 22 states that do not require sexual education to be medically accurate.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Comprehensive sexual education has been proven to work to reduce the risk of teen pregnancies.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Without a nationwide mandate for medically accurate programs, teenagers in the United States are at risk of missing out on valuable information that can protect them.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] It is unfair to expect teenagers to make educated decisions about sex that can lead to teen pregnancy when they have never been properly educated about the issue.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A program developed by experts in public health and sexual education titled *National Sexuality Education Standards,* is a valuable resource that describes what the minimum requirements of sexual education should be across the nation.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Giving teenagers the tools that are outlined in that roadmap would have positive effects, as it gives teenagers the resources to make educated decisions.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Currently, there is no national implementation of this program in the United States.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teen pregnancy can be reduced by sex education, as a 2022 study in 55 US counties showed.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The study used federally funded sex education programs as a proxy for sex education, but provided no details about funding levels, the number of students reached, or the amount of time spent on sex education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The reduction of teenage births, not pregnancy, was significant, with a 3% reduction, indicating that an increase in funding, education, or reach could decrease teenage pregnancy even further.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Although 3% sounds like a small number, given a teenage girl population of 10 million females aged 15–19 in 2020, and ~190,000 teenage births per year, a 3% reduction would translate to about 6,000 prevented teenage births per year when extrapolated to the whole nation.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Some schools provide abstinence-only sex education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Evidence does not support the effectiveness of abstinence-only sex education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] It has been found to be ineffective in decreasing HIV risk in the developed world, and does not decrease rates of unplanned pregnancy when compared to comprehensive sex education.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] It does not decrease the sexual activity rates of students, when compared to students who undertake comprehensive sexual education classes.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Nurse-Family Partnership (NFP) is a non-profit organization operating in the United States and the UK designed to serve the needs of young mothers who may have special needs in their first pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Each mother served is partnered with a registered nurse early in her pregnancy and receives ongoing nurse home visits that continue through her child's second birthday.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] NFP intervention has been associated with improvements in maternal health, child health, and economic security.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2018, Québec's Institut national de santé publique (INSPQ) began implementing adjustments to the Protocole de contraception du Québec (Québec Contraception Protocol).
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The new protocol allows registered nurses to prescribe hormonal birth control, an IUD, or emergency birth control to women, as long as they comply with prescribed standards in the Prescription infirmière: Guide explicatif conjoint, and are properly trained in providing contraceptives.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2020, Québec will offer online training to registered nurses, provided by the Ordre des infirmières et infirmiers du Québec (OIIQ).
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Nurses who do not have training in the areas of sexually transmitted and blood-borne infections may have to take additional online courses provided by the INSPQ.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the US, one policy initiative that has been used to increase rates of contraceptive use is Title X.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Title X of the Family Planning Services and Population Research Act of 1970 (Pub.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In September 2010, the US Department of Health and Human Services approved $155 million in new funding for comprehensive sex education programs designed to prevent teenage pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The money is being awarded "to states, non-profit organizations, school districts, universities, and others.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the developing world, programs of reproductive health aimed at teenagers are often small-scale and not centrally coordinated, although some countries, such as Sri Lanka, have a systematic policy framework for teaching about sex within schools.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Non-governmental agencies such as the International Planned Parenthood Federation and Marie Stopes International provide contraceptive advice for young women worldwide.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Laws against child marriage have reduced but not eliminated the practice.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Improved female literacy and educational prospects have led to an increase in the age at first birth in areas such as Iran, Indonesia, and the Indian state of Kerala.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In reporting teenage pregnancy rates, the number of pregnancies per 1,000 females aged 15 to 19, when the pregnancy ends, is generally used.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2003, worldwide teenage pregnancy rates ranged from 143 per 1,000 in some sub-Saharan African countries to 2.9 per 1,000 in South Korea.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the US in 2013, 82% of pregnancies in those between 15 and 19 were unplanned.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Among OECD developed countries in 2001, the US, the UK and New Zealand had the highest level of teenage pregnancy, while Japan and South Korea had the lowest.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] According to the UNFPA, "In every region of the world – including high-income countries – poor girls, poorly educated or living in rural areas are at greater risk of becoming pregnant than those who are wealthier, well-educated or urban.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] This is true on a global level, as well: 95 percent of the world's births to adolescents (aged 15–19) take place in developing countries.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In a 2001 UNICEF survey, in 10 out of 12 developed nations with available data, more than two-thirds of young people have had sexual intercourse while still in their teens.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In Denmark, Finland, Germany, Iceland, Norway, the UK, and the US, the proportion is over 80%.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In Australia, the UK, and the US, approximately 25% of 15-year-olds and 50% of 17-year-olds have had sex.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2004, approximately 15 million girls under the age of 20 in the world had a child each year.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Estimates were that 20–60% of these pregnancies in developing countries are mistimed or unwanted.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] UNICEF noted that these declines were "tied to improvements in almost all regional rates".
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2004, Save the Children found that, annually, 13 million children are born to women aged under 20 worldwide, with more than 90% in developing countries.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Complications of pregnancy and childbirth are the leading causes of mortality among women aged 15–19 in such areas.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The highest rate of teenage pregnancy in the world is in sub-Saharan Africa, where women tend to marry at an early age.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2023, in Western and Central Africa, and Eastern and Southern Africa, over 25% of adolescent girls and young women gave birth before age 18.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In these regions, this amounts to an estimated 11 million young women.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In Niger in 1999, 87% of women surveyed were married and 53% had given birth to a child before the age of 18.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 2018 study found that socio-cultural factors, economic factors, environmental factors, individual factors, and health service-related factors were responsible for the high rates of teenage pregnancy in Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the Indian subcontinent, early marriage sometimes results in adolescent pregnancy, particularly in rural regions where the rate is much higher than it is in urbanized areas.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2008, teen pregnancy in India was high, with 62 pregnant teens out of every 1,000 women.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] India is fast approaching to be the most populous country in the world by 2050 and increasing teenage pregnancy, an important factor for the population rise, is likely to aggravate the problems.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The rates of early marriage and pregnancy in some Asian countries are high.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the 2000s, the rates decreased sharply in Indonesia and Malaysia, although it remains relatively high in Indonesia.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the industrialized Asian nations such as South Korea and Singapore, teenage birth rates remain among the lowest in the world.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2015, the birth rate among teenage women in Australia was 11.9 births per 1,000 women.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The rate has fallen from 55.5 births per 1,000 women in 1971, probably due to ease of access to effective birth control, rather than any decrease in sexual activity.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The overall trend in Europe since 1970 has been a decreasing total fertility rate, an increase in the age at which women experience their first birth, and a decrease in the number of births among teenagers.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Most continental Western European countries have very low teenage birth rates.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] This is varyingly attributed to good sex education and high levels of contraceptive use (in the case of the Netherlands and Scandinavia), traditional values and social stigmatization (in the case of Spain and Italy) or both (in the case of Switzerland).
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] On the other hand, the teen birth rate is very high in Bulgaria and Romania.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2015, Bulgaria had a birth rate of 37 per 1,000 women aged 15–19.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Romania had a birth rate of 34 per 1,000 women aged 15–19.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The teen birth rate of these two countries is even higher than that of underdeveloped countries like Burundi and Rwanda.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Many of the teen births occur in Roma populations, who have an occurrence of teenage pregnancies well above the local average.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The teen pregnancy rate in England and Wales was 23.3 per 1,000 women aged 15 to 17.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] There were 5,740 pregnancies in girls aged under 18 in the three months to June 2014, data from the Office for National Statistics shows.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] This compares with 6,279 in the same period in 2013 and 7,083 for the June quarter of the year before that.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Historically, the UK has had one of the highest teenage pregnancy and abortion rates in Western Europe.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] There are no comparable rates for conceptions across Europe, but the under-18 birth rate suggests England is closing the gap.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The under-18 birth rate in 2012 in England and Wales was 9.2, compared with an EU average of 6.9.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] However, the UK birth rate has fallen by almost a third (32.3%) since 2004, compared with a fall of 15.6% in the EU.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2004, the UK rate was 13.6 births per 1,000 women aged 15–17 compared with an EU average rate of 7.7.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2001, the teenage birth rate in the US was the highest in the developed world, and the teenage abortion rate is also high.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2005, 57% of teen pregnancies resulted in a live birth, 27% ended in an induced abortion, and 16% in a fetal loss.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The US teenage pregnancy rate was at a high in the 1950s and has decreased since then, although there has been an increase in births out of wedlock.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The teenage pregnancy rate decreased significantly in the 1990s.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] This decline was across all racial groups.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenagers of African-American and Hispanic descent retain a higher rate of teen pregnancy, in comparison to that of European-Americans and Asian-Americans.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2006, the Guttmacher Institute attributed about 25% of the decline to abstinence and 75% to the effective use of contraceptives.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2006, the US teen birth rate rose for the first time in fourteen years.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2010, it reached a historic low: 34.3 births per 1,000 women aged 15–19.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Given a teenage girl population of 10 million females, aged 15–19, in 2020, this would translate to ~190,000 births per year.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2009, the Latina teenage pregnancy rate was 75% higher than the national average.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2012, the states with the highest teenage birthrates were Mississippi, New Mexico, and Arkansas.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 2012, the states with the lowest teenage birthrate were New Hampshire, Massachusetts, and Vermont.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Between 1992 and 2002, the Canadian teenage birth rate steadily declined for both younger (15–17) and older (18–19) teens.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In Canada, the stability of familial structure significantly influences the risk of teenage pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In a 2018 study, experiencing one or more episodes of poverty before the age of 13 made young Canadian girls 75% to 90% more vulnerable to teenage pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In some cases, the father of the child is the partner of the teenage girl.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] The conception may occur within wedlock, or the pregnancy itself may precipitate the marriage, the so-called shotgun wedding.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In countries such as India, the majority of teenage births occur within marriage.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the US and Ireland, the majority of teenage mothers are not married to the father of their children.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the UK, half of all teenagers with children are lone parents, 40% are cohabitating as a couple, and 10% are married.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Teenage parents are frequently in a romantic relationship at the time of birth, but many adolescent fathers do not stay with the mother, and this often disrupts their relationship with the child.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] US surveys tend to under-report the prevalence of teen fatherhood.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In many cases, "teenage father" may be a misnomer.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] Studies in the 1990s found that about two-thirds of births to teenage girls in the US are fathered by adult men aged over 20.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In 1995, the Guttmacher Institute reported that over 40% of mothers aged 15–17 had sexual partners three to five years older, and almost one in five had partners six or more years older.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] A 1990 study of births to California teens reported that the younger the mother, the greater the age gap with her male partner.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p01] In the UK in 2005, in 72% of jointly registered births to women aged under 20, the father is over 20, with almost 1 in 4 being over 25.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] Teenage pregnancy remains a significant social and cultural issue in many countries around the world.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] While the rate of teenage pregnancies has declined in recent decades, it continues to be a cause for concern, both from a health perspective and in terms of its impact on the lives of young people.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] The causes of teenage pregnancy are complex and multifaceted, reflecting the interplay between individual behavior, societal norms and cultural attitudes.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] In many cultures, there is a lack of comprehensive sexual education, which contributes to a lack of understanding about contraception and sexually transmitted infections.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] There is also a cultural stigma attached to discussing sexual health and relationships, which makes it difficult for young people to access the information and support they need.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] Poverty, lack of access to healthcare, and limited opportunities for education and employment can also contribute to the high rate of teenage pregnancy.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] These factors can make it difficult for young people to make informed choices about their sexual health and can limit their ability to access contraception and other forms of protection.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] The effects of some of the teenage they get pregnancy can be far-reaching and long-lasting.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] Pregnant teenagers are at increased risk of health problems, including complications during pregnancy and childbirth, and are more likely to experience poverty and limited opportunities later in life.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] Their children are also more likely to experience health and developmental problems, and to grow up in poverty.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] Despite these challenges, there are many programs and initiatives aimed at reducing the rate of teenage pregnancy and supporting young people who become pregnant.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] These efforts include comprehensive sex education programs, access to contraception and family planning services, and support for young mothers.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] Teenage pregnancy is a complex issue that reflects the interplay between individual behavior, societal norms, and cultural attitudes.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] Addressing this issue requires a comprehensive approach that includes education, access to healthcare, and support for young people.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] By working together, we can help to reduce the rate of teenage pregnancy and improve the lives of young people and their families.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] Some politicians condemn pregnancy in unmarried teenagers as a drain on taxpayers, if the mothers and children receive welfare payments and social housing from the government.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] In 1989, singer Terry Tate, a former teacher and graduate from Seton Hall University, used his knowledge of issues concerning young students at his school which included teenage pregnancy to compose the song, *"Babies Having Babies"*.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] Radio stations became involved in trying to get the message across.
[src:breast-binding/adolescent-pregnancy-p02] It ended up being a national hit on the *Billboard* and *Cash Box* charts in 1989.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Unlike guardianship or other systems designed for the care of the young, adoption is intended to effect a permanent change in status and as such requires societal recognition, either through legal or religious sanction.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Historically, some societies have enacted specific laws governing adoption, while others used less formal means (notably contracts that specified inheritance rights and parental responsibilities without an accompanying transfer of filiation).
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Modern systems of adoption, arising in the 20th century, tend to be governed by comprehensive statutes and regulations.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] While the modern form of adoption emerged in the United States, forms of the practice appeared throughout history.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The Code of Hammurabi, for example, details the rights of adopters and the responsibilities of adopted individuals at length.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The practice of adoption in ancient Rome is well-documented in the Codex Justinianus.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Markedly different from the modern period, ancient adoption practices put emphasis on the political and economic interests of the adopter, providing a legal tool that strengthened political ties between wealthy families and created male heirs to manage estates.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The use of adoption by the aristocracy is well-documented: many of Rome's emperors were adopted sons.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Adrogation was a kind of Roman adoption in which the person adopted consented to be adopted by another.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Infant adoption during Antiquity appears rare.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Abandoned children were often picked up for slavery and composed a significant percentage of the Empire's slave supply.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Roman legal records indicate that foundlings were occasionally taken in by families and raised as a son or daughter.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Although not normally adopted under Roman Law, the children, called *alumni*, were reared in an arrangement similar to guardianship, being considered the property of the father who abandoned them.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Other ancient civilizations, notably India and China, used some form of adoption as well.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Evidence suggests the goal of this practice was to ensure the continuity of cultural and religious practices; in contrast to the Western idea of extending family lines.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In ancient India, adoption was conducted in a limited and highly ritualistic form, so that an adopter might have the necessary funerary rites performed by a son.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] China had a similar idea of adoption with males adopted solely to perform the duties of ancestor worship.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The practice of adopting the children of family members and close friends was common among the cultures of Polynesia including Hawaii where the custom was referred to as *hānai*.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The nobility of the Germanic, Celtic, and Slavic cultures that dominated Europe after the decline of the Roman Empire denounced the practice of adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In medieval society, bloodlines were paramount; a ruling dynasty lacking a "natural-born" heir apparent was replaced, a stark contrast to Roman traditions.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The evolution of European law reflects this aversion to adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] English common law, for instance, did not permit adoption since it contradicted the customary rules of inheritance.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In the same vein, France's Napoleonic Code made adoption difficult, requiring adopters to be over the age of 50, sterile, older than the adopted person by at least 15 years, and to have fostered the adoptee for at least six years.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Some adoptions continued to occur, however, but became informal, based on ad hoc contracts.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] For example, in the year 737, in a charter from the town of Lucca, three adoptees were made heirs to an estate.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Like other contemporary arrangements, the agreement stressed the responsibility of the adopted rather than adopter, focusing on the fact that, under the contract, the adoptive father was meant to be cared for in his old age; an idea that is similar to the conceptions of adoption under Roman law.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Europe's cultural makeover marked a period of significant innovation for adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Without support from the nobility, the practice gradually shifted toward abandoned children.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Abandonment levels rose with the fall of the empire and many of the foundlings were left on the doorstep of the Church.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Initially, the clergy reacted by drafting rules to govern the exposing, selling, and rearing of abandoned children.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The Church's innovation, however, was the practice of oblation, whereby children were dedicated to lay life within monastic institutions and reared within a monastery.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] This created the first system in European history in which abandoned children did not have legal, social, or moral disadvantages.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] As a result, many of Europe's abandoned and orphaned children became alumni of the Church, which in turn took the role of adopter.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Oblation marks the beginning of a shift toward institutionalization, eventually bringing about the establishment of the foundling hospital and orphanage.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] As the idea of institutional care gained acceptance, formal rules appeared about how to place children into families: boys could become apprenticed to an artisan and girls might be married off under the institution's authority.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Institutions informally adopted out children as well, a mechanism treated as a way to obtain cheap labor, demonstrated by the fact that when the adopted died their bodies were returned by the family to the institution for burial.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] This system of apprenticeship and informal adoption extended into the 19th century, today seen as a transitional phase for adoption history.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Under the direction of social welfare activists, orphan asylums began to promote adoptions based on sentiment rather than work; children were placed out under agreements to provide care for them as family members instead of under contracts for apprenticeship.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The growth of this model is believed to have contributed to the enactment of the first modern adoption law in 1851 by the Commonwealth of Massachusetts, unique in that it codified the ideal of the "best interests of the child".
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Despite its intent, though, in practice, the system operated much the same as earlier incarnations.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The experience of the Boston Female Asylum (BFA) is a good example, which had up to 30% of its charges adopted out by 1888.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The next stage of adoption's evolution fell to the emerging nation of the United States.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Rapid immigration and the American Civil War resulted in unprecedented overcrowding of orphanages and foundling homes in the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Charles Loring Brace, a Protestant minister, became appalled by the legions of homeless waifs roaming the streets of New York City.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Brace considered the abandoned youth, particularly Catholics, to be the most dangerous element challenging the city's order.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] His solution was outlined in *The Best Method of Disposing of Our Pauper and Vagrant Children* (1859), which started the Orphan Train movement.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The orphan trains eventually shipped an estimated 200,000 children from the urban centers of the East to the nation's rural regions.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The children were generally indentured, rather than adopted, to families who took them in.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] As in times past, some children were raised as members of the family while others were used as farm laborers and household servants.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The sheer size of the displacement—one of the largest migrations of children in history—and the degree of exploitation that occurred, gave rise to new agencies and a series of laws that promoted adoption arrangements rather than indenture.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The hallmark of the period is Minnesota's adoption law of 1917, which mandated investigation of all placements and limited record access to those involved in the adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] During the same period, the Progressive movement swept the United States with a critical goal of ending the prevailing orphanage system.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] As late as 1923, only two percent of children without parental care were in adoptive homes, with the balance in foster arrangements and orphanages.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Less than forty years later, nearly one-third were in adoptive homes.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Nevertheless, the popularity of eugenic ideas in America put up obstacles to the growth of adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] There were grave concerns about the genetic quality of illegitimate and indigent children, perhaps best exemplified by the influential writings of Henry H.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The period 1945 to 1974, the baby scoop era, saw rapid growth and acceptance of adoption as a means to build a family.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Illegitimate births rose three-fold after World War II, as sexual mores changed.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Simultaneously, the scientific community began to stress the dominance of nurture over genetics, chipping away at eugenic stigmas.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In this environment, adoption became the obvious solution for infertile couples.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Many of the mothers, however, were forced or coerced into relinquishing their children.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Taken together, these trends resulted in a new American model for adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Following its Roman predecessor, Americans severed the rights of the original parents while making adopters the new parents in the eyes of the law.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The origin of the move toward secrecy began with Charles Loring Brace, who introduced it to prevent children from the Orphan Trains from returning to or being reclaimed by their parents.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Brace feared the impact of the parents' poverty, in general, and Catholic religion, in particular, on the youth.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] This tradition of secrecy was carried on by the later Progressive reformers when drafting of American laws.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The number of adoptions in the United States peaked in 1970.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The years of the late 1960s and early 1970s saw a dramatic change in society's view of illegitimacy and in the legal rights of those born outside of wedlock.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In response, family preservation efforts grew so that few children born out of wedlock today are adopted.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Ironically, adoption is far more visible and discussed in society today, yet it is less common.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The American model of adoption eventually proliferated globally.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] England and Wales established their first formal adoption law in 1926.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Sweden made adoptees full members of the family in 1959.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] West Germany enacted its first laws in 1977.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Additionally, the Asian powers opened their orphanage systems to adoption, influenced as they were by Western ideas following colonial rule and military occupation.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In France, local public institutions accredit candidates for adoption, who can then contact orphanages abroad or ask for the support of NGOs.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The system does not involve fees, but gives considerable power to social workers whose decisions may restrict adoption to "standard" families (middle-age, medium to high income, heterosexual, Caucasian).
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The table below provides a snapshot of Western adoption rates.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Adoption in the United States still occurs at rates nearly three times those of its peers even though the number of children awaiting adoption has held steady in recent years, between 100,000 and 125,000 during the period 2009 to 2018.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Contemporary adoption practices can be open or closed.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Adoptions can occur between related or unrelated individuals.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Historically, most adoptions occurred within a family.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The most recent data from the U.S. indicates that about half of adoptions are currently between related individuals.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] A common example of this is a "step-parent adoption", where the new partner of a parent legally adopts a child from the parent's previous relationship.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Intra-family adoption can also occur through surrender, as a result of parental death, or when the child cannot otherwise be cared for and a family member agrees to take over.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Adoption is not always a voluntary process.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In some countries, for example in the U.K., one of the main origins of children being placed for adoption is that they have been removed from the birth home, often by a government body such as the local authority.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] There are a number of reasons why children are removed including abuse and neglect, which can have a lasting impact on the adoptee.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Social workers in many cases will be notified of a safeguarding concern in relation to a child and will make enquiries into the child's well-being.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Social workers will often seek means of keeping a child together with the birth family, for example, by providing additional support to the family before considering removal of a child.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] A court of law will often then make decisions regarding the child's future, for example, whether they can return to the birth family, enter into foster care or be adopted.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Infertility is the main reason parents seek to adopt children they are not related to.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] One study shows this accounted for 80% of unrelated infant adoptions and half of adoptions through foster care.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Estimates suggest that 11–24% of Americans who cannot conceive or carry to term attempt to build a family through adoption, and that the overall rate of never-married American women who adopt is about 1.4%.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Other reasons people adopt are numerous although not well documented.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Although there are a range of reasons, the most recent study of experiences of women who adopt suggests they are most likely to be 40–44 years of age, to be currently married, to have impaired fertility, and to be childless.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Although adoption is often described as forming a "forever" family, the relationship can be ended at any time.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The legal termination of an adoption is called disruption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In U.S. terminology, adoptions are *disrupted* if they are ended before being finalized, and they are *dissolved* if the relationship is ended afterwards.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] It may also be called a *failed adoption*.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] After legal finalization, the disruption process is usually initiated by adoptive parents via a court petition and is analogous to divorce proceedings.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] It is a legal avenue unique to adoptive parents as disruption/dissolution does not apply to biological kin, although biological family members are sometimes disowned or abandoned.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The wide range of values reflects the paucity of information on the subject and demographic factors such as age; it is known that teenagers are more prone to having their adoptions disrupted than young children.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Joint adoption by same-sex couples is legal in 34 countries as of March 2022, and additionally in various sub-national territories.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Adoption may also be in the form of stepchild adoption (6 additional countries), wherein one partner in a same-sex couple adopts the child of the other.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Most countries that have same-sex marriage allow joint adoption by those couples, the exceptions being Ecuador (no adoption by same-sex couples), Taiwan (stepchild adoption only) and Mexico (in one third of states with same-sex marriage).
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] A few countries with civil unions or lesser marriage rights nonetheless allow step- or joint adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In 2019, the American Community Survey (ACS) enhanced its approach to measuring same-sex couple households, explicitly distinguishing between same-sex and opposite-sex spouses or partners.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Same-sex parents, according to the ACS in 2022, were predominantly female.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Notably, 26.8% of female same-sex couple households had children under 18, in contrast to 8.2% of male same-sex couple households.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In homes with children, female same-sex couples were almost 12% more likely to have biological children compared with male same-sex couples; however, male same-sex couples were 18.5% more likely to adopt and were less likely to have stepchildren.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] The biological relationship between a parent and child is important, and the separation of the two has led to concerns about adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] This theory is supported in another more qualitative study wherein adoptive relationships marked by sameness in likes, personality, and appearance, were associated with both adult adoptees and adoptive parents reporting being happier with the adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Other studies provide evidence that adoptive relationships can form along other lines.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Noting that adoptees seemed to be more likely to experience problems such as drug addiction, the study speculated that adoptive parents might invest more in adoptees not because they favor them, but because they are more likely than genetic children to need the help.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Psychologists' findings regarding the importance of early mother-infant bonding created some concern about whether parents who adopt older infants or toddlers after birth have missed some crucial period for the child's development.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Beyond the foundational issues, the unique questions posed for adoptive parents are varied.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] They include how to respond to stereotypes, answering questions about heritage, and how best to maintain connections with biological kin when in an open adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] One author suggests a common question adoptive parents have is: "Will we love the child even though he/she is not our biological child?" A specific concern for many parents is accommodating an adoptee in the classroom.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Familiar lessons like "draw your family tree" or "trace your eye color back through your parents and grandparents to see where your genes come from" could be hurtful to children who were adopted and do not know this biological information.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Numerous suggestions have been made to substitute new lessons, e.g., focusing on "family orchards".
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Adopting older children presents other parenting issues.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Some children from foster care have histories of maltreatment, such as physical and psychological neglect, physical abuse, and sexual abuse, and are at risk of developing psychiatric problems.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Such children are at risk of developing a disorganized attachment.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] (1990, 1995) found that 80% of abused and maltreated infants in their sample exhibited disorganized attachment styles.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Disorganized attachment is associated with a number of developmental problems, including dissociative symptoms, as well as depressive, anxious, and acting-out symptoms.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] "Attachment is an active process—it can be secure or insecure, maladaptive or productive." In the U.K., some adoptions fail because the adoptive parents do not get sufficient support to deal with difficult, traumatized children.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] This is a false economy as local authority care for these children is extremely expensive.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Similar mechanisms appear to be at work in the physical development of adoptees.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Danish and American researchers conducting studies on the genetic contribution to body mass index found correlations between an adoptee's weight class and his biological parents' BMI while finding no relationship with the adoptive family environment.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Moreover, about one-half of inter-individual differences were due to individual non-shared influences.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] These differences in development appear to play out in the way young adoptees deal with major life events.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In the case of parental divorce, adoptees have been found to respond differently from children who have not been adopted.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Recent research has shown that adoptive parenting may have impacts on adoptive children, it has been shown that warm adoptive parenting reduces internalizing and externalizing problems of the adoptive children over time.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Another study shows that warm adoptive parenting at 27 months predicted lower levels of child externalizing problems at ages 6 and 7.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Several factors affect the decision to release or raise the child.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] White adolescents tend to give up their babies to non-relatives, whereas black adolescents are more likely to receive support from their own community in raising the child and also in the form of informal adoption by relatives.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Studies by Leynes and by Festinger and Young, Berkman, and Rehr found that, for pregnant adolescents, the decision to release the child for adoption depended on the attitude toward adoption held by the adolescent's mother.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Another study found that pregnant adolescents whose mothers had a higher level of education were more likely to release their babies for adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Research suggests that women who choose to release their babies for adoption are more likely to be younger, enrolled in school, and have lived in a two-parent household at age 10, than those who kept and raised their babies.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] There is limited research on the consequences of adoption for the original parents, and the findings have been mixed.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] One study found that those who released their babies for adoption were less comfortable with their decision than those who kept their babies.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] However, levels of comfort over both groups were high, and those who released their child were similar to those who kept their child in ratings of life satisfaction, relationship satisfaction, and positive future outlook for schooling, employment, finances, and marriage.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Subsequent research found that adolescent mothers who chose to release their babies for adoption were more likely to experience feelings of sorrow and regret over their decision than those who kept their babies.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] However, these feelings decreased significantly from one year after birth to the end of the second year.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] More recent research found that in a sample of mothers who had released their children for adoption four to 12 years prior, every participant had frequent thoughts of their lost child.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] For most, thoughts were both negative and positive in that they produced both feelings of sadness and joy.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Those who experienced the greatest portion of positive thoughts were those who had open, rather than closed or time-limited mediated, adoptions.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] In another study that compared mothers who released their children to those who raised them, mothers who released their children were more likely to delay their next pregnancy, to delay marriage, and to complete job training.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] However, both groups reached lower levels of education than their peers who were never pregnant.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Another study found similar consequences for choosing to release a child for adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Adolescent mothers who released their children were more likely to reach a higher level of education and to be employed than those who kept their children.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] They also waited longer before having their next child.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Most of the research that exists on adoption effects on the birth parents was conducted with samples of adolescents, or with women who were adolescents when carrying their babies—little data exists for birth parents from other populations.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p01] Furthermore, there is a lack of longitudinal data that may elucidate long-term social and psychological consequences for birth parents who choose to place their children for adoption.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Previous research on adoption has led to assumptions that indicate that there is a heightened risk in terms of psychological development and social relationships for adoptees.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Yet, such assumptions have been clarified as flawed due to methodological failures.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] But more recent studies have been supportive in indicating more accurate information and results about the similarities, differences and overall lifestyles of adoptees.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Adoptees are four times more likely to attempt suicide than other people.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Evidence about the development of adoptees can be supported in newer studies.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] It can be said that adoptees, in some respect, tend to develop differently from the general population.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] This can be seen in many aspects of life, but usually can be found as a greater risk around the time of adolescence.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] For example, it has been found that many adoptees experience difficulty in establishing a sense of identity.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] There are many ways in which the concept of identity can be defined.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] It is true in all cases that identity construction is an ongoing process of development, change and maintenance of identifying with the self.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Research has shown that adolescence is a time of identity progression rather than regression.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] One's identity tends to lack stability in the beginning years of life but gains a more stable sense in later periods of childhood and adolescence.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Typically associated with a time of experimentation, there are endless factors that go into the construction of one's identity.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] As well as being many factors, there are many types of identities one can associate with.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Some categories of identity include gender, sexuality, class, racial and religious, etc.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] For transracial and international adoptees, tension is generally found in the categories of racial, ethnic and national identification.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Because of this, the strength and functionality of family relationships play a huge role in its development and outcome of identity construction.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Transracial and transnational adoptees tend to develop feelings of a lack of acceptance because of such racial, ethnic, and cultural differences.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Therefore, exposing transracial and transnational adoptees to their "cultures of origin" is important in order to better develop a sense of identity and appreciation for cultural diversity.
[src:breast-binding/adoption-p02] Identity construction and reconstruction for transnational adoptees the instant they are adopted.
